Citation.Description: Property which controls the propagation of a seismic wave at a particular (non-zero) angle of incidence. It is a function of the material density, the compressional wave velocity within the material, the ratio between the shear and the compressional wave velocities, and the angle of incidence. This property, analogous to Acoustic_Impedance but for non-zero incidence angles, is described in 1998 SEG Paper "Calibration and Inversion of Non-Zero Offset Seismic Data", by Patrick Connolly (BP).

Citation.Description: Effective frequency range, typically between the half-power points (the frequencies at which the power drops to half of the peak power). Bandwidth is occasionally represented by the central frequency of the band or as the difference between the lower and upper limits of the frequency band, but generally the absolute frequencies should be specified, such as by using Band_Low/High_Frequency properties or by using a complex value type with the Bandwidth property.
Citation.Title: bandwidth

Citation.Description: Statistical estimation of bandwidth of data within window. Aids in determining appropriate spectral operators for subsequent operations. Computation: Let the autocorrelation of the trace be A[i]. Then compute M = max(A) and S = sum(A[i]**2). The bandwidth rating bias B is then : B = M**2 / r(2 S - M**2), where r is the sample rate.
Citation.Title: bandwidth rating bias

Citation.Description: Statistical estimation of bandwidth of data within window. The bandwidth rating debias D is computed from the bandwidth rating bias B as follows: D = 5/3 B - 1/(s*n), where n is the number of sampled used in the computation. Generally more stable than Bandwidth_Rating_Bias, unless window is small.
Citation.Title: bandwidth rating debias

Citation.Description: It is common in an interbedded reservoir for sands thinner than a certain cutoff thickness (Min_Net_Thickness) to be discarded as non net or non pay in a ResSum type analysis. However, a thick sand may have two closely spaced shale stringers, such that they create the effect of a thin sand separated from thick sands above and below by thin shale beds. In this case, if the shale beds are thinner than a second thickness threshold (Min_Non_Net_Thickness), the thin sand would be counted as net or pay.

Citation.Title: orientation

Citation.Description: The line or course on which something is moving or is aimed to move or along which something is pointing or facing.
Citation.Title: direction

Citation.Description: Direction of fluid flow through the sample in the laboratory (e.g. Horizontal, Downwards, Upwards). Water-oil experiments are almost always horizontal, gas-liquid experiments may be horizontal or vertical. If they are vertical they are done in the gravity stable direction. For example gas flooding an oil filled plug would be downwards, water flooding a gas filled plug would be upwards.
Citation.Title: scal flood direction

Citation.Description: The orientation of a shoreline pertaining to the local paleontology.
Citation.Title: local paleo shoreline orient

Citation.Description: The perforation density; i.e., the number of shots per unit length.

Citation.Description: A property of rock (formation) denoting its ability to pass fluids through its interconnected pores.
Citation.Title: permeability

Citation.Description: The permeability of porous material when completely saturated with a wetting fluid and without the influence of non-Darcy (turbulence) effects. Also called "intrinsic" permeability.
Citation.Title: absolute permeability

Citation.Description: The permeability of porous material when completely saturated with gas.
Citation.Title: absolute permeability gas

Citation.Description: The permeability of porous material when completely saturated with oil.
Citation.Title: absolute permeability oil

Citation.Description: The permeability of porous material when completely saturated with water.
Citation.Title: absolute permeability water

Citation.Description: Empirical permeability measure derived by extrapolating the trend of gas permeability versus inverse pressure to infinite pressure (zero inverse pressure). The result is equivalent to the permeability which would be measured if the sample were 100% saturated with a non-reactive liquid and is sometimes called "liquid permeability" and abbreviated KL (where L is a subscript).
Citation.Title: klinkenberg permeability

Citation.Description: Permeability of the Crushed Zone around perforation
Citation.Title: crushed zone permeability

Citation.Description: Permeability of the near-wellbore Damaged Zone, the sandface layer around the wellbore where permeability and mobility are impaired, generally by a damaging material (e.g. completion or drill mud).
Citation.Title: damaged zone permeability

Citation.Description: An oriented permeability within a porous media, expressed either as horizontal (along the bedding plane of the stratum) or vertical (perpendicular to the bedding plane of the stratum), or within a coordinate system.
Citation.Title: directional permeability

Citation.Description: A permeability oriented horizontally along the bedding plane of the stratum. Usually abbreviated as Kx.
Citation.Title: horizontal permeability

Citation.Description: Permeability measured along the length of a core cylinder.
Citation.Title: permeability axial path

Citation.Description: Permeability measured in the plane transverse to the length of the core cylinder. This may be represented as a single measurement in the flow plane or as a two component permeability represented as a measurement along an arbitrary diameter and another along an orthogonal path in the same plane.
Citation.Title: permeability transverse path

Citation.Description: An effective permeability used to combine directional permeabilities, Kx and Ky. Usually abbreviated as Ksph.
Citation.Title: spherical permeability

Citation.Description: A permeability oriented vertically perpendicular to the bedding plane of the stratum. Usually abbreviated as Ky.
Citation.Title: vertical permeability

Citation.Description: Permeability in X Direction
Citation.Title: x direction permeability

Citation.Description: Permeability in Y Direction
Citation.Title: y direction permeability

Citation.Description: The measure of the capacity of a single fluid to flow through a rock when the pore spaces of the rock are not completely filled or saturated with the fluid.
Citation.Title: effective permeability

Citation.Description: The measure of the capacity of gas to flow through a rock when the pore spaces of the rock contain other fluids.
Citation.Title: effective permeability gas

Citation.Description: Effective permeability to gas at residual oil saturation.
Citation.Title: effective permeability gas sor

Citation.Description: Effective permeability to gas at initial water saturation.
Citation.Title: effective permeability gas swi

Citation.Description: Effective permeability to gas at residual water saturation.
Citation.Title: effective permeability gas swr

Citation.Description: The measure of the capacity of oil to flow through a rock when the pore spaces of the rock contain other fluids.
Citation.Title: effective permeability oil

Citation.Description: Effective permeability to oil at initial water saturation.
Citation.Title: effective permeability oil swi

Citation.Description: The measure of the capacity of water to flow through a rock when the pore spaces of the rock contain other fluids.
Citation.Title: effective permeability water

Citation.Description: Effective permeability to water at residual oil saturation.
Citation.Title: effective permeability water sor

Citation.Description: Mean permeability in horizontal or vertical plane, computed as the square root of the product of the normal directional permeability values (e.g. X-Y or Y-Z) in the plane.
Citation.Title: geometric mean permeability

Citation.Description: Geometric mean permeability in the horizontal plane (X-Y) of the reservoir.
Citation.Title: horizontal mean permeability

Citation.Description: Geometric mean permeability in the vertical plane (Y-Z) of the reservoir
Citation.Title: vertical mean permeability

Citation.Description: Minimum value of Permeability
Citation.Title: min permeability

Citation.Description: Average permeability in the net pay portion of the zone interval (thickness weighted arithmetic average).
Citation.Title: net pay permeability

Citation.Description: Average permeability in the Net Reservoir portion of the summation interval, computed from core data by point-match method.
Citation.Title: net reservoir core permeability point match

Citation.Description: Average permeability in the Net Reservoir portion of the summation interval, computed from log data by point-match method.
Citation.Title: net reservoir log permeability point match

Citation.Description: Average permeability in the net reservoir portion of the zone interval (thickness weighted arithmetic/geometric/harmonic average).
Citation.Title: net reservoir permeability

Citation.Description: Formation permeability as measured with an nuclear magnetic logging device.
Citation.Title: nmr permeability

Citation.Description: The ratio of effective permeability divided by the absolute permeability; e.g. the relative permeability of a rock to that of any of its contained fluids.
Citation.Title: relative permeability

Citation.Description: Ratio of effective gas permeability to absolute permeability. Usually abbreviated as Krg
Citation.Title: relative permeability gas

Citation.Description: Ratio of effective oil permeability to absolute permeability. Usually abbreviated as Kro.
Citation.Title: relative permeability oil

Citation.Description: Ratio of effective water permeability to absolute permeability. Usually abbreviated as Krw.
Citation.Title: relative permeability water

Citation.Description: Prepensity of a material to conduct magnetic flux; inverse of reluctance. Units of inductance but not the same property
Citation.Title: permeance

Citation.Description: The property of a material that enables it to store electrical charge, typically measured in farad/m. Free space has a Permittivity of 8.854E-12 farad/m.
Citation.Title: permittivity

Citation.Description: The ratio of the Permittivity of a material to that of free space.
Citation.Title: dielectric constant

Citation.Description: A measure of the probability that scattering due the Photoelectric Effect will occur; often expressed in an approximation unit barns/electron.
Citation.Title: photoelectric factor

Citation.Description: Photoelectric Factor of the filter cake (mudcake); often expressed in an approximation unit barns/electron.
Citation.Title: filter cake photoelectric factor

Citation.Description: Photoelectric Factor of the matrix (zero-porosity rock) or pure material; often expressed in an approximation unit barns/electron.
Citation.Title: matrix photoelectric factor

Citation.Description: The angular displacement between two lines extending from the same point, measured in the plane of the two lines.
Citation.Title: plane angle

Citation.Description: The maximum reading (deflection) taken from a direct-reading viscometer after the fluid has been quiescent for 1 minutes.
Citation.Title: 1 minute gel test deflection

Citation.Description: The maximum reading (deflection) taken from a direct-reading viscometer after the fluid has been quiescent for 10 minutes.
Citation.Title: 10 minute gel test deflection

Citation.Description: The maximum reading (deflection) taken from a direct-reading viscometer after the fluid has been quiescent for 10 seconds.
Citation.Title: 10 second gel test deflection

Citation.Description: The maximum reading (deflection) taken from a direct-reading viscometer after the fluid has been quiescent for 30 minutes.
Citation.Title: 30 minute gel test deflection

Citation.Description: Horizontal angle measured clockwise from true North. (Also referred to as True Bearing.) Occasionally azimuth will be specified relative to some other reference.
Citation.Title: azimuth

Citation.Description: Azimuth of the axis, usually pertaining to a depositional environment such as a tidal-flat.
Citation.Title: axis azimuth

Citation.Description: The azimuth of the point at which borehole failure starts.
Citation.Title: borehole failure azimuth

Citation.Description: Azimuth of central line of projection.
Citation.Title: central line bearing

Citation.Description: The azimuth of an object with respect to magnetic north.
Citation.Title: compass bearing

Citation.Description: Azimuth of the direction of maximum dip of a surface; dip may be computed in several ways, including from logs, from well-to-well correlation, from gradients on interpreted time or depth surfaces, etc.

Citation.Description: Pressure, represented as the height of a column of dense fluid that can be supported by the pressure.

Citation.Description: Initial reservoir pressure, before any production or injection occurs, normally abbreviated Pi; sometimes taken as the pressure at the external boundary of the drainage area.

Citation.Description: Pressure at the inlet of an equipment item.

Citation.Description: Pressure observed at kill line/BOP.

Citation.Description: Maximum pressure which an equipment can withstand without permanent damage at standard temperature.

Citation.Description: Maximum working pressure of the outer equipment

Citation.Description: Maximum pressure
Citation.Title: max pressure

Citation.Description: Maximum pressure to which this Equipment can be exposed for a short time without permanent damage; the Equipment will again perform to specifications when the pressure is reduced below the maximum working pressure.

Citation.Description: The pressure of the fluid contained in the pore volume.

Citation.Description: A measure of the tendency of a permeable stratum to exhibit vertical equilibrium of flowing fluids, defined as: (length / height) * SQRT(kv/kh), where length is the characteristic length of the flow path and height is the gross or net height.

Citation.Description: The ratio of the useful energy delivered by a dynamic system to the energy supplied to it.
Citation.Title: efficiency

Citation.Description: The fraction of displaceable fluids/hydrocarbons that has been actually displaced when contacted by a displacing fluid.
Citation.Title: displacement efficiency

Citation.Description: Ratio of Fracture Volume at end of job to Total Volume Pumped. The difference between the two volumes represents the volume which leaked off into the formation.
Citation.Title: fracturing efficiency

Citation.Description: Ratio of mass rate of HGS (high Gravity Solid) discarded through the underflow of a piece of SCE (Solids Control Equipment) to the mass rate of HGS fed into it
Citation.Title: hgs removal efficiency

Citation.Description: Ratio of the mass rate of LGS (low gravity solid) in the underflow of a piece of SCE (Solids Control Equipment) to the mass rate of LGS fed into it
Citation.Title: lgs removal efficiency

Citation.Description: Characterization of relative distribution of energy in a layer, computed as the fractional displacement (depth or time) into an interval (layer, bed) where half of the energy is above, half below.

Citation.Description: Depth, within a specified interval, at which half the energy of the interval occurs
Citation.Title: energy half depth

Citation.Description: Time, within a specified interval, at which half the energy of the interval occurs
Citation.Title: energy half time

Citation.Description: Ratio of the ellipse of uncertainty cone radius increase per depth increment
Citation.Title: eou cone growth ratio

Citation.Description: Ratio of the count rate of the near detector to that of the far detector in an epithermal neutron logging device

Citation.Description: The equilibrium vaporization ratio, or ratio of the mole fraction of a fluid system component in the vapor phase divided by the mole fraction of the same component in the liquid phase.

Citation.Description: Ratio of fault transmissibility to formation transmissibility.
Citation.Title: fault transmissibility

Citation.Description: Fraction of the fracture permeability retained at in-situ conditions after taking into account the damage due to fluid residue, function of the breaker, gel concentration and temperature at closure. Has the same effect as Proppant_Permeability_Factor.
Citation.Title: fluid permeability factor

Citation.Description: Ratio of two forces
Citation.Title: force per force

Citation.Description: Ratio of the resistivity of water-saturated rock to that of the water solution contained in the rock. Also called Formation Resistivity Factor and abbreviated "F".
Citation.Title: formation resistivity factor

Citation.Description: Unitless fraction of an image that is displayed above the depth associated with the image.
Citation.Title: fraction above depth point

Citation.Description: Ratio of fracture width to mean proppant diameter (Industry usage: 2.5.) below which bridging will occur (proppant cannot move through the fracture).
Citation.Title: fracture bridging factor

Citation.Description: The ratio of normal compliance of the fracture to the total normal compliance of the fractured rock. It indicates how much of the total compliance of the fractured rock is due to the fractures. See Compliance.
Citation.Title: fracture normal weakness

Citation.Description: The ratio of shear compliance of the fracture to the total shear compliance of the fractured rock. It indicates how much of the total compliance of the fractured rock is due to the fractures. See Compliance.
Citation.Title: fracture shear weakness

Citation.Description: Ratio of the frictional (tangential) force to the contact (normal) force between two objects or materials in contact.

Citation.Description: Friction coefficient due to rotation between casing and other surface (e.g. drill string).
Citation.Title: casing rotation friction coefficient

Citation.Description: Friction coefficient due to sliding between casing and other surface (e.g. drill string), when only sliding motion is present
Citation.Title: casing sliding friction coefficient

Citation.Description: Linear component of the friction coefficient between casing and drill string during an helical movement, e.g., reaming mode
Citation.Title: casing translation friction coefficient

Citation.Description: Ratio of contact and friction forces between 2 materials in dry friction conditions i.e. without lubrication (Coulomb law)
Citation.Title: coulomb friction coefficient

Citation.Description: Friction coefficient between a string and the borehole when pulling out of the hole
Citation.Title: pickup friction coefficient

Citation.Description: Friction coefficient between a string and the pipe when running into the hole
Citation.Title: slackoff friction coefficient

Citation.Description: Friction coefficient between open hole and drill string in rotation
Citation.Title: hole rotation friction coefficient

Citation.Description: Friction coefficient between open hole and drill string in sliding (translation only) operating mode
Citation.Title: hole sliding friction coefficient

Citation.Description: Vertical component of the Friction coefficient between open hole and drill string during an helical movement, e.g., reaming mode
Citation.Title: hole translation friction coefficient

Citation.Description: Ratio of the stored gas in the kerogen (solid hydrocarbon) to the total gas stored in the system
Citation.Title: gas sorption storativity ratio

Citation.Description: The ratio of any two far-field principal stresses in the earth; see subtypes.
Citation.Title: geostress ratio

Citation.Description: Ratio of maximum horizontal to minimum horizontal stress. (Normally abbreviated SH/Sh)
Citation.Title: max horizontal to min horizontal geostress ratio

Citation.Description: Ratio of minimum horizontal to vertical stress. (Normally abbreviated Sh/SV)
Citation.Title: min horizontal to vertical geostress ratio

Citation.Description: Ratio of early-time (initial) to final wellbore storage factor ("Ca/C")
Citation.Title: initial final wellbore storage ratio

Citation.Description: The isotope ratio is a value that puts into relation a measured isotope quantity versus another isotope of the same component and compares it to a standard
Citation.Title: isotope ratio

Citation.Description: Describes the adsorption of hydrocarbon compounds on kerogen
Citation.Title: kerogen adsorption

Citation.Description: Ratio of layer storativity to total storativity ("omegaj")
Citation.Title: layer storativity ratio

Citation.Description: Ratio of layer transmissibility to total transmissibility ("kappaj")
Citation.Title: layer transmissibility ratio

Citation.Description: Ratio of two lengths
Citation.Title: length per length

Citation.Description: Ratio of Litho_Thickness to Gross_Thickness of a reservoir summation interval.

Citation.Description: The ratio of a distance measured on a map to the actual distance. It is normally expressed as a unitless ratio (e.g. 1:1000), or as the product of a unitless ratio and the ratio of two units (e.g. 1 in = 5 mile, or .2 in/mi).
Citation.Title: map scale

Citation.Description: The ratio of the mass of a component to the total mass.
Citation.Title: mass fraction

Citation.Description: Ratio of memory used to total memory.
Citation.Title: memory usage

Citation.Description: Ratio of the mobility of one system or layer (permeability divided by viscosity) to that of another system or layer.

Citation.Description: Ratio volume of N2 over foam volume . Indicator of the quality of a foam generated with N2 for well treatment. Below 50% the foam is not stable, above 95% the foam changes to a mist.

Citation.Description: Ratio of Net_Thickness to Gross_Thickness

Citation.Description: Ratio of Net_Reservoir_Thickness to Gross_Thickness

Citation.Description: The ratio of noise amplitude to signal amplitude, usually expressed in dB. Note: the inverse, Signal_To_Noise_Ratio, is preferred and should be used whenever possible.

Citation.Description: Fraction to which the equipment is open, e.g., 50% open

Citation.Description: Ratio of amplitudes of two peaks.

Citation.Description: Ratio of amplitudes of peak and trough.

Citation.Description: Ratio of component permeability-thickness to total system permeability-thickness [kh(i) / kh(total)], usually known as Kappa in reservoir dynamics work.

Citation.Description: Ratio of the transverse contraction of a body to its longitudinal extension when stretched. Typical values in minerals are from 0.15 to 0.3 (Carbonates:0.15, Sandstones:0.2, Shales:0.25).

Citation.Description: Ratio of number of positive samples to total number of samples. Equivalent to Threshold_Ratio where threshold is zero.

Citation.Description: The ratio of the sum of layer porosity thicknesses to total system porosity thicknesses for a layered porous media.

Citation.Description: Productivity ratio (actual productivity index divided by ideal (zero skin) productivity index)

Citation.Description: The ratio of one part of an amount to the whole, with respect to quantity or magnitude.

Citation.Description: Percentage of interest held by one of the potentially many organizations holding a lease agreement.

Citation.Description: Percentage of rock occupied by conductive beds within a given depth interval

Citation.Description: Ratio of amount of sample or material recovered to total amount recoverable.

Citation.Description: The pressure of a fluid divided by the critical pressure of the fluid.

Citation.Description: The temperature of a fluid divided by the critical temperature of the fluid.

Citation.Description: Ratio of the displacement amplitude of a reflected wave to that of the incident wave. Also called Reflectivity.

Citation.Description: Reflectivity due to changes in elastic impedance

Citation.Description: Reflectivity due to changes in compressional impedance

Citation.Description: Reflectivity due to changes in shear impedance

Citation.Description: The ratio of signal amplitude to noise amplitude, usually expressed in dB.

Citation.Description: Ratio of fissure storativity to total system storativity. Usually known as Omega in reservoir dynamics.

Citation.Description: Ratio of component storativity-thickness to total system storativity-thickness [phi*Ct*h(i) / phi*Ct*h(total)].

Citation.Description: A measurement of the resistivity of the formation, by a spherically focused tool, within the first few inches of the borehole wall.
Citation.Title: micro spherically focused resistivity

Citation.Description: Mineral Resistivity
Citation.Title: mineral resistivity

Citation.Description: Resistivity of mud filtrate
Citation.Title: mud filtrate resistivity

Citation.Description: Apparent resistivity of the mud filtrate, generally from log measurements of the "flushed zone".
Citation.Title: apparent mud filtrate resistivity

Citation.Description: Resistivity of Drilling Fluid, also known as mud.
Citation.Title: mud resistivity

Citation.Description: Resistivity of the mud at Bottomhole Conditions
Citation.Title: bottomhole mud resistivity

Citation.Description: The electrical resistivity of mud going into the hole, usually measured in the active circulating pit
Citation.Title: mud resistivity in

Citation.Description: The electrical resistivity of mud coming out of the hole, usually measured in the ditch before the shale shakers
Citation.Title: mud resistivity out

Citation.Description: Resistivity profile measurement, used primarily for pattern recognition; may or may not be calibrated.
Citation.Title: profile resistivity

Citation.Description: The ratio of apparent resistivity to the true resistivity of a portion of a reservoir model (like a two-layer model).
Citation.Title: relative apparent resistivity

Citation.Description: The resistivity which represents a measurement made approximately one to two feet into the formation; generally considered to measure the formation where it contains fluids which are comprised primarily of mud filtrate.
Citation.Title: shallow resistivity

Citation.Description: The resistivity, measured by an induction log, which represents a measurement made approximately one to two feet into the formation; generally considered to measure the formation where it contains fluids which are comprised primarily of mud filtrate.
Citation.Title: shallow induction resistivity

Citation.Description: Resistivity measurement using a "lateral" electrode arrangement with a "shallow" investigation radius (several inches into the formation).
Citation.Title: shallow lateral resistivity

Citation.Description: The resistivity, measured by a laterolog (or guard log) resistivity device, which represents a measurement made approximately one to two feet into the formation; generally considered to measure the formation where it contains fluids which are comprised primarily of mud filtrate.
Citation.Title: shallow laterolog resistivity

Citation.Description: Shallow Resistivity measurement using a "normal" electrode arrangement.
Citation.Title: shallow normal resistivity

Citation.Description: The resistivity, measured by a spherically focused log, which represents the resistivity approximately one to two feet into the formation.
Citation.Title: spherically focused resistivity

Citation.Description: Resistivity of connate (formation) water
Citation.Title: water resistivity

Citation.Description: Apparent resistivity of connate (formation) water, generally from logs; such estimates require correction before they can be used quantitatively.
Citation.Title: apparent water resistivity

Citation.Description: K Factor, a function of the geometry of the electrode or sensor array of a resistivity measurement device.
Citation.Title: resistivity k factor

Citation.Description: Sensor response equation
Citation.Title: response equation

Citation.Description: Amount by which some operating condition could be exceeded before reaching the theoretical operational limit, to allow for uncertainty in the actual upper limit. For upper limits, Operating Condition X (1 + Safety Factor) = Upper Limit.
Citation.Title: safety factor

Citation.Description: Amount by which borehole pressure should remain below fracture pressure, to allow for uncertainty in fracture pressure estimation.
Citation.Title: fracture pressure safety factor

Citation.Description: Amount by which borehole pressure should normally exceed pore pressure, to allow for uncertainty in pore pressure estimation.
Citation.Title: pore pressure safety factor

Citation.Description: Volume in excess of what has been calculated for the job. Used to account for loss or safety margin
Citation.Title: volume safety factor

Citation.Description: Weight in excess of what has been calculated for the job. Used to account for loss or safety margin
Citation.Title: weight safety factor

Citation.Description: Index interval between sequential data samples; see also Depth_Increment and Time_Increment (Sampling_Period)
Citation.Title: sample interval

Citation.Description: The fraction or percentage of the pore volume occupied by a specific fluid; e.g., oil, gas, water.
Citation.Title: saturation

Citation.Description: The extent to which the pore space in a formation contains bound water.
Citation.Title: bound water saturation

Citation.Description: The extent to which the pore space in a flushed zone around the borehole contains bound water.
Citation.Title: flushed zone bound water saturation

Citation.Description: The value of saturation of a specific fluid phase at which the fluid will first begin to flow as saturation is increased.
Citation.Title: critical saturation

Citation.Description: The value of gas saturation at which gas will begin to flow, as gas saturation is increased.
Citation.Title: critical gas saturation

Citation.Description: The value of oil saturation at which oil will begin to flow, as oil saturation is increased.
Citation.Title: critical oil saturation

Citation.Description: The highest water saturation a hydrocarbon-producing rock can maintain before water will begin to flow.
Citation.Title: critical water saturation

Citation.Description: The extent to which the pore space in a flushed zone around the borehole contains fluid.
Citation.Title: flushed zone fluid saturation

Citation.Description: The extent to which the pore space in a flushed zone around the borehole contains hydrocarbons.
Citation.Title: flushed zone hydrocarbon saturation

Citation.Description: The extent to which the pore space in a flushed zone around the borehole contains oil based mud filtrate.
Citation.Title: flushed zone obmf saturation

Citation.Description: The extent to which the pore space in a flushed zone around the borehole contains water.
Citation.Title: flushed zone water saturation

Citation.Description: Average flushed zone water saturation in the net pay portion of the zone (thickness weighted arithmetic average).
Citation.Title: net pay flushed zone water saturation

Citation.Description: Average flushed zone water saturation in the net reservoir portion of the zone (thickness weighted arithmetic average).
Citation.Title: net reservoir flushed zone water saturation

Citation.Description: The extent to which the pore space in a formation contains gas.
Citation.Title: gas saturation

Citation.Description: Gas saturation at the breakthrough point. In Special Core Analysis, breakthrough is the appearance of the injected fluid at the outlet face of the rock sample.
Citation.Title: gas saturation at breakthrough

Citation.Description: The gas saturation at minimum oil saturation in a three phase system. (SCAL SGM)
Citation.Title: gas saturation min so 3phase

Citation.Description: Gas Saturation at the beginning of the test, experiment or production.
Citation.Title: initial gas saturation

Citation.Description: The fraction of pore volume filled with hydrocarbons.
Citation.Title: hydrocarbon saturation

Citation.Description: The fraction of the pore volume occupied by water in a reservoir at maximum hydrocarbon saturation, such that it cannot be further reduced.
Citation.Title: irreducible water saturation

Citation.Description: The fraction of the total pore volume in a formation or rock sample occupied by liquid.
Citation.Title: liquid saturation

Citation.Description: The fraction of the total pore volume in a rock sample occupied by mercury (special core analysis)
Citation.Title: mercury saturation

Citation.Description: The extent to which the pore space in a formation contains oil.
Citation.Title: oil saturation

Citation.Description: Oil Saturation at the beginning of the test, experiment or production.
Citation.Title: initial oil saturation

Citation.Description: Minimum oil saturation in a 3 phase system. (SCAL SORM)
Citation.Title: min oil saturation 3phase

Citation.Description: The fraction or percentage of gas remaining following production from the reservoir.
Citation.Title: residual gas saturation

Citation.Description: The fraction or percentage of hydrocarbons remaining following the production of hydrocarbons from the reservoir.
Citation.Title: residual hydrocarbon saturation

Citation.Description: The fraction or percentage of oil remaining following the liberation of gases from the reservoir.
Citation.Title: residual oil saturation

Citation.Description: The fraction or percentage of water remaining at maximum hydrocarbon saturation, as measured in core analysis. It differs from Irreducible_Water_Saturation because of filtrate invasion and gas expansion from the core being brought to the surface.
Citation.Title: residual water saturation

Citation.Description: The extent to which the pore space in a formation contains water.
Citation.Title: water saturation

Citation.Description: Water Saturation at the beginning of the test, experiment or production.
Citation.Title: initial water saturation

Citation.Description: Maximum value of Water Saturation
Citation.Title: max water saturation

Citation.Description: Average water saturation in the net pay portion of the zone (thickness weighted arithmetic average).
Citation.Title: net pay water saturation

Citation.Description: Average water saturation in the Net Reservoir portion of the summation interval, computed from core data by point-match method.
Citation.Title: net reservoir core water saturation point match

Citation.Description: Average water saturation in the Net Reservoir portion of the summation interval, computed from log data by point-match method.
Citation.Title: net reservoir log water saturation point match

Citation.Description: Average water saturation in the net reservoir portion of the zone (thickness weighted arithmetic average).
Citation.Title: net reservoir water saturation

Citation.Description: Water saturation at the breakthough point. In Special Core Analysis, breakthough is the appearance of the injected fluid at the outlet face of the rock sample.
Citation.Title: water saturation at breakthrough

Citation.Description: Water saturation at the breakthough point, calculated from fractional flow curve (SCAL SwBkFF). In Special Core Analysis, breakthough is the appearance of the injected fluid at the outlet face of the rock sample.
Citation.Title: water saturation at breakthrough ff

Citation.Description: The water saturation at minimum oil saturation in a three phase system. (SCAL SWM)
Citation.Title: water saturation min so 3phase

Citation.Description: A geometrical property of an area which reflects how its points are distributed with regard to an arbitrary axis
Citation.Title: second moment of area

Citation.Description: The term that accounts for additional pressure drops in the immediate vicinity of a well in well performance calculations. A positive skin indicates damaged conditions, negative indicates stimulated conditions.
Citation.Title: skin factor

Citation.Description: Skin effect due the completion of the producing interval. It does not include the effect of partially completed interval (plugged perf or bad localization), but it does include Gravel Pack skin.
Citation.Title: completion skin

Citation.Description: The skin effect caused by the well trajectory not being perpendicular to the bedding plane.
Citation.Title: deviation skin

Citation.Description: The skin effect caused by mechanical or chemical formation damage such as invasion of drilling fluids, migration of fine material, wettability change, scale deposit or bacteria. The annular volume damaged is called the Damaged Zone.
Citation.Title: formation damage skin

Citation.Description: The skin along the face of the fracture (natural or hydraulic).
Citation.Title: fracture face skin

Citation.Description: Matrix to natural fracture skin factor in a naturally fractured system.
Citation.Title: matrix block skin

Citation.Description: Sum of Completion_Skin, Formation_Damage_Skin including anything limiting the flow across the completed interval. Does not include Partial_Completion_Skin.
Citation.Title: mechanical skin

Citation.Description: The skin effect resulting from turbulent flow conditions within the reservoir or the completion. This is the only skin which is flowrate dependent.
Citation.Title: non darcy skin

Citation.Description: The skin effect caused by flow convergence due to not completing the entire flowing thickness. Does not include the skin due to the completion itself.
Citation.Title: partial completion skin

Citation.Description: The sum of all formation, completion, deviation, geometric and fluid flow skin factors. It can be a function of the flowrate if a Non-Darcy skin effect is present.
Citation.Title: total skin

Citation.Description: In a horizontal well, skin effect due to the limited entry in the vertical direction.
Citation.Title: vertical geometric skin

Citation.Description: Highest rate of change in signal level which a device can produce; also the rate at which a device reacts to commands. In the latter case, the data are normally represented in units of time.
Citation.Title: slew rate

Citation.Description: A measure of the field of view from some specific vantage point occupied by an object.
Citation.Title: solid angle

Citation.Description: A measure of the amount of one substance (the solute) which will dissolve in a given amount of another (the solvent).
Citation.Title: solubility

Citation.Description: Measure of the degree to which a gas is soluble in water, often designated Rs Water
Citation.Title: gas water solubility

Citation.Description: Amount of rock, normally expressed as a percentage by weight soluble in a given acid
Citation.Title: rock solubility in acid

Citation.Description: Amount of rock, normally expressed as a percentage by weight soluble in HCl
Citation.Title: rock solubility in hcl

Citation.Description: Amount of rock, normally expressed as a percentage by weight soluble in Mud Acid (standard mixture of 12 % HCl and 3% HF)
Citation.Title: rock solubility in rma

Citation.Description: The source of an entity instance, usually a user name or an application (or activity) instance.
Citation.Title: source

Citation.Description: The source of information used to detect dips (e.g., Seismic data, Structural analysis, Dipmeter log data, etc.)
Citation.Title: dip detection source

Citation.Description: The source of the data used to detect faults (e.g., Seismic data, Structural analysis, Dipmeter log data, etc.)
Citation.Title: fault detection source

Citation.Description: General location from which a fluid sample was taken (test line, mud pit)
Citation.Title: fluid sample origin

Citation.Description: Specify where interpretation was performed on data.
Citation.Title: interpretation origin

Citation.Description: Name of a declination survey, a vendor of declination data, a reference book, or a person supplying the value.
Citation.Title: magnetic declination source

Citation.Description: A data set of sparse location data in 2-space, where none or up to n Properties may be represented at each location. Example: X_Coordinate,Y_Coordinate,Porosity,Density.
Citation.Title: sparse 2d data

Citation.Description: A data set of sparse location data in 3-space, where none or up to n Properties may be represented at each location. Example: X_Coordinate,Y_Coordinate,Z_Coordinate,Velocity.
Citation.Title: sparse 3d data

Citation.Description: Radioactive activity per unit mass
Citation.Title: specific activity (of radioactivity)

Citation.Description: The amount of heat in calories required to raise the temperature of 1 gram of substance by 1 degree Celsius.
Citation.Title: specific heat

Citation.Description: Heat capacity per unit of mass
Citation.Title: specific heat capacity

Citation.Description: The change in specific heat capacity with temperature
Citation.Title: specific heat capacity per temperature

Citation.Description: Change in aggregate heat capacity of an object with respect to temperature
Citation.Title: heat capacity per temperature

Citation.Description: The cube of the change in specific heat capacity with temperature
Citation.Title: specific heat capacity per temperature cubed

PropertyKind.QuantityClass: PWLS:specific heat capacity per temperature cubed

Citation.Description: The cube of the change in aggregate heat capacity of an object with respect to temperature
Citation.Title: heat capacity per temperature cubed

Parent.Title: specific heat capacity per temperature cubed

PropertyKind.QuantityClass: PWLS:specific heat capacity per temperature cubed

Citation.Description: The square of the change in specific heat capacity with temperature
Citation.Title: specific heat capacity per temperature squared

PropertyKind.QuantityClass: PWLS:specific heat capacity per temperature squared

Citation.Description: The square of the change in aggregate heat capacity of an object with respect to temperature
Citation.Title: heat capacity per temperature squared

Parent.Title: specific heat capacity per temperature squared

PropertyKind.QuantityClass: PWLS:specific heat capacity per temperature squared

Citation.Description: The characteristic of a porous media which is the internal surface area of the medium per unit volume.
Citation.Title: specific surface area

Citation.Description: The characteristic of a porous media which is the internal surface area of the medium per unit mass.
Citation.Title: specific surface area per mass

Citation.Description: The characteristic of a porous media which is the internal surface area of the medium per unit volume.
Citation.Title: specific surface area per volume

Citation.Description: A measure of the volume distribution of a gas or liquid per unit mass.
Citation.Title: specific volume

Citation.Description: Gas volume required to make a unit mass; the reciprocal of density
Citation.Title: gas volume per mass

Citation.Description: Volume of gas production per mass in coal, for example the Langmuir volume constant.
Citation.Title: coal gas volume per mass

Citation.Description: Intensity of light emitted by a material represented as a function of emitted light wavelength and wavelength of the excitation beam, typically an ultraviolet light source.
Citation.Title: spectral fluorescence intensity

Citation.Description: Coefficient relating spiral spring exerted force and corresponding elongation
Citation.Title: spring stiffness

Citation.Description: Square root pressure
Citation.Title: square root pressure

Citation.Description: The Hildebrand solubility parameter is the square root of the cohesive energy density and used in petroleum systems to describe the solubility of hydrocarbon components in water
Citation.Title: square root energy per volume

Citation.Description: Residual static information (time) for each station
Citation.Title: station residual static

Citation.Description: A property of statistical nature, e.g. Standard Deviation, Average or Mean, Median, etc.
Citation.Title: statistical property

Citation.Description: The extent to which a measurement approaches the true value of a quantity; usually expressed as a fraction of the true value or, for instrumentation, full scale.
Citation.Title: accuracy

Citation.Description: The maximum difference, over the calibrated range, between pressure applied to the gauge, with a reference standard, and the pressure measured by the gauge.
Citation.Title: pressure accuracy

Citation.Description: The maximum difference, over the calibrated range, between temperature applied to the gauge, with a reference standard, and the temperature measured by the gauge.
Citation.Title: temperature accuracy

Citation.Description: The accuracy attached to the transit time measurement or computation.
Citation.Title: transit time accuracy

Citation.Description: Statistical test of data distribution, used to measure goodness of fit of the data to some distribution model.
Citation.Title: chi square

Citation.Description: A measure of the common variance between two quantities; a non-normalized crosscorrelation function.
Citation.Title: covariance

Citation.Description: The deviation of a measurement from the true value; usually expressed as an absolute quantity rather than as a fraction; the unit quantity is determined by that of the data.
Citation.Title: error

Citation.Description: Plus or minus azimuth error of sensor
Citation.Title: azimuth error

Citation.Description: Departure (error) from the exact setting of a feedback loop
Citation.Title: feedback loop deviation

Citation.Description: Plus or minus inclination error of sensor
Citation.Title: inclination error

Citation.Description: Error in NMR window sum or raw echo fitting.
Citation.Title: nmr fitting error

Citation.Description: An unwanted portion of the total conductivity measurement of an induction logging instrument, generated by imperfections in the coils in the sonde. It is measured during surface calibration and then cancelled during the survey operation.
Citation.Title: sonde error

Citation.Description: Tolerance range within which the measurement should remain; the sum of the positive and negative tolerances. May be scaled in measurement units or expressed as a proportion of the instrument rating.
Citation.Title: error band

Citation.Description: A measure of the sharpness of a population distribution. If X10, X25, X75 and X90 are the values for which 10, 25, 75, and 90 percent of the population is smaller, respectively, then kurtosis = (X75 - X25) / 2(X90 - X10).
Citation.Title: kurtosis

Citation.Description: Kurtosis of seismic amplitude (normalized).
Citation.Title: amplitude kurtosis

Citation.Description: Generic property for a measure of how well the actual data fit a model of the expected values and/or distribution of data. Standard measures include Standard Deviation, Variance, Chi-Square.
Citation.Title: model fit error

Citation.Description: Normalized property derived by a statistical algorithm normalizing between 0. and 1. the original values of some numerical data; the original data Property code and normalization range may be documented in Remarks.
Citation.Title: normalized quantity

Citation.Description: The repeatability of an instrument measured by the mean deviation of a set of measurements from the average value; the unit quantity is determined by that of the data.
Citation.Title: precision

Citation.Description: Statistical standard deviation from the mean value for some data; normally abbreviated a lowercase sigma; the unit quantity is determined by that of the data.
Citation.Title: standard deviation

Citation.Description: Standard deviation of seismic amplitude.
Citation.Title: amplitude standard deviation

Citation.Description: A statistical measure of asymmetry in a distribution.
Citation.Title: statistical skewness

Citation.Description: Skewness of seismic amplitude (normalized).
Citation.Title: amplitude skewness

Citation.Description: Allowable uncertainty or deviation from a standard; the unit quantity is determined by that of the data value.
Citation.Title: tolerance

Citation.Description: Amount of negative tolerance on a measurement value; the unit quantity is determined by that of data value.
Citation.Title: minus tolerance

Citation.Description: Amount of positive tolerance on a measurement value; the unit quantity is determined by that of data value.
Citation.Title: plus tolerance

Citation.Description: Precision with which a measurement is known; often implies a 50-50 chance that any one of a series of measurements will fall within a given range; the unit quantity is determined by that of data value. Uncertainty is not necessarily related to Accuracy.
Citation.Title: uncertainty

Citation.Description: Uncertainty of a Length measurement.
Citation.Title: length uncertainty

Citation.Description: Uncertainty of a time measurement.
Citation.Title: time uncertainty

Citation.Description: Magnitude of uncertainty for a measurement being represented as a position in 2D or 3D coordinate space, such as a geographical position.
Citation.Title: uncertainty radius

Citation.Description: Uncertainty of a velocity measurement.
Citation.Title: velocity uncertainty

Citation.Description: A measure of the width of the probability distribution for a single random variable; the square of standard deviation.
Citation.Title: variance

Citation.Description: The ratio of stress acting in a specified direction to the strain in a specified direction. Stiffness is a tensor of rank 4, but is expressible as a 6x6 matrix, the inverse of the compliance matrix.
Citation.Title: stiffness

Citation.Description: Product of Porosity and Total Compressibility for a reservoir hydraulic unit.
Citation.Title: storativity

Citation.Description: Fracture Storativity (Porosity * Total Compressibility product) of a finite conductivity vertical fracture ("(phi*Ct)f")
Citation.Title: fracture storativity

Citation.Description: The product of the Storativity of a layer and its thickness [phi*Ct*h].
Citation.Title: storativity thickness

Citation.Description: Inter-well Storativity-Thickness [phi*Ct*h] for a horizontal interference test.
Citation.Title: interwell storativity thickness

Citation.Description: Sum of the Storativity_Thickness values of all layers in the model.
Citation.Title: total storativity thickness

Citation.Description: Measure of the change in dimensions or shape caused by stress, generally expressed as a unitless ratio of the change of length per unit of initial length. If not otherwise specified, strain is taken to be "normal" (in the same direction as the stress).
Citation.Title: strain

Citation.Description: Shear component of the change in dimensions caused by stress, generally expressed as a unitless ratio.
Citation.Title: shear strain

Citation.Description: Force acting per unit area in a material resisting the stretching, compression or shear induced by external forces; fully characterized by a Stress_Tensor.
Citation.Title: stress

Citation.Description: Effective Stress of completed interval
Citation.Title: eff formation stress

Citation.Description: Formation minimum principal stress, the smallest of the 3 components of the diagonal stress tensor (fractures will propagate perpendicular to its direction). Can be defaulted to Frac Gradient x TVD. Can be output from DataFRAC treatment.
Citation.Title: min in situ stress

Citation.Description: Shear force (shear: strain that causes contiguous parts of a body to slide relatively to each other in a direction parallel to their plane of contact) per area unit of surface
Citation.Title: shear stress

Citation.Description: Shear Stress required to break a gel fluid previously allowed to remain at rest for 1 minute.
Citation.Title: 1 minute gel strength

Citation.Description: Shear Stress required to break a gel fluid previously allowed to remain at rest for 10 minutes.
Citation.Title: 10 minute gel strength

Citation.Description: Shear Stress required to break a gel fluid previously allowed to remain at rest for 10 seconds.
Citation.Title: 10 second gel strength

Citation.Description: Shear Stress required to break a gel fluid previously allowed to remain at rest for 30 minutes.
Citation.Title: 30 minute gel strength

Citation.Description: Resistance to initial flow; the stress required to start fluid movement. Specifically, shear stress at 0 shear rate for Bingham Plastic (BP) rheological model, otherwise named Bingham yield value or yield point. BP fluid remains static until applied forces build up to the point where it starts to move. See Plastic_Viscosity.
Citation.Title: yield stress

Citation.Description: Resistance to initial flow; the stress required to start fluid movement. When using the direct-indicating viscometer, it is found by subtracting plastic viscosity (API_Plastic_Viscosity) from the 300-rpm reading of a Fann35 rheometer.
Citation.Title: api yield stress

Citation.Description: Resistance to initial flow; the stress required to start fluid movement. The Casson model equation is: SQRT(Shear_Stress) = SQRT(Yield_Stress) + SQRT(Plastic_Viscosity X Shear_Rate)
Citation.Title: casson yield stress

Citation.Description: A second rank tensor whose components are the stresses exerted across surfaces perpendicular to the coordinate directions.
Citation.Title: stress tensor

Citation.Description: Normalized sum of the square of the differences of principal stresses applied to a material, e.g. for coiled tubing hoop, bending and radial. See Von_Mises_To_Yield_Ratio.
Citation.Title: von mises stress

Citation.Description: The amount of stretch per unit force applied.
Citation.Title: stretch coefficient

Citation.Description: Measure of the two-dimensional extent of the surface of some object.
Citation.Title: surface area

Citation.Description: Average area of conductive inclusions as seen at the borehole wall
Citation.Title: conductive inclusion size

Citation.Description: The cross-sectional area of an object; e.g., area of perforation in a cased borehole.
Citation.Title: cross section area

Citation.Description: Cross sectional area of a pipe
Citation.Title: pipe cross sectional area

Citation.Description: The drainage area of a reservoir.
Citation.Title: drainage area

Citation.Description: Gross area of a region such as that of a lease parcel or covered by a lease agreement.
Citation.Title: gross area

Citation.Description: Average area of resistive inclusions as seen at the borehole wall
Citation.Title: resistive inclusion size

Citation.Description: Total cross-sectional area through which fluid can flow.
Citation.Title: total flow area

Citation.Description: An artificial seismic section produced by collecting artificially-generated traces (such as a Synthetic_Seismogram from log-derived Reflectivity) or by extracting data from an actual seismic section.
Citation.Title: synthetic seismic section

Citation.Description: An artificial seismic reflection record produced by assuming a particular wavelet and model. Commonly, a one dimensional synthetic seismogram is generated by convolving a typical seismic wavelet with log-derived Reflectivity.
Citation.Title: synthetic seismogram

Citation.Description: Tape density, usually expressed in bits per inch.
Citation.Title: tape density

Citation.Description: The degree of hotness or coldness measured on a definite scale
Citation.Title: temperature

Citation.Description: Temperature at which recording should begin
Citation.Title: activation temperature

Citation.Description: The temperature at which fractions of a liquid boil.
Citation.Title: boiling point

Citation.Description: The temperature at the bottom of a borehole occurring at the time of the activity being performed on the well.
Citation.Title: bottomhole temperature

Citation.Description: The bottom hole temperature reached when circulating. Due to the cooling effect of the drill fluid, BHCT is below the BHST.
Citation.Title: bottomhole circulating temperature

Citation.Description: Temperature at the bottom of the well while flowing.
Citation.Title: bottomhole flowing temperature

Citation.Description: The bottom hole equilibrium temperature (when circulation is stopped)
Citation.Title: bottomhole static temperature

Citation.Description: The temperature at reservoir conditions at which gas in solution in crude oil comes out of solution as free gas.
Citation.Title: bubble point temperature

Citation.Description: Temperature of the cooling fluid
Citation.Title: coolant temperature

Citation.Description: The highest temperature at which a fluid can exist as a liquid and above which its vapor cannot be liquefied regardless of the amount of pressure. Applies to pure components; for mixtures use Pseudocritical_Temperature.
Citation.Title: critical temperature

Citation.Description: The highest temperature at which a gas can exist as a liquid and above which its vapor cannot be liquefied regardless of the amount of pressure (Dry gas = free gas without condensate)
Citation.Title: dry gas critical temperature

Citation.Description: The highest temperature at which a fluid can exist as a liquid and above which its vapor cannot be liquefied regardless of the amount of pressure. Used for mixtures, analogous to Critical_Temperature for pure components.
Citation.Title: pseudocritical temperature

Citation.Description: The highest temperature at which the gas can exist as a liquid and above which its vapor cannot be liquefied regardless of the amount of pressure (Wet gas - mixture of free gas plus condensate)
Citation.Title: wet gas critical temperature

Citation.Description: The difference in temperature between two objects or materials.
Citation.Title: differential temperature

Citation.Description: Engine lubrication Oil Temperature
Citation.Title: engine oil temperature

Citation.Description: The temperature at which the Fann test was performed.
Citation.Title: fann test temperature

Citation.Description: Final temperature of shipping bottle
Citation.Title: final transfer temperature

Citation.Description: The temperature of a fluid (sample) under certain conditions.

Citation.Description: Temperature of the material in the borehole.

Citation.Description: The temperature of a mud or drilling fluid (sample) under certain conditions.

Citation.Description: The temperature of mud coming out of the hole, usually measured in the ditch before the shale shakers
Citation.Title: mud temperature out

Citation.Description: The temperature of oil under certain conditions.
Citation.Title: oil temperature

Citation.Description: Temperature of the (earth) formations.

Citation.Description: Temperature of gelled fluid (fracturing gel, gelled acid ...)
Citation.Title: gel temperature

Citation.Description: Temperature of the hydraulic fluid delivered to an Hydraulic motor
Citation.Title: hydraulic drive temperature

Citation.Description: Temperature taken when initial reservoir pressure recorded
Citation.Title: initial reservoir pressure temperature

Citation.Description: Maximum operating temperature for an equipment item.
Citation.Title: max operating temperature

Citation.Description: Maximum Storage Temperature
Citation.Title: max storage temperature

Citation.Description: Maximum Temperature to which this Equipment can be exposed for a short time without permanent damage; the Equipment will again perform to specifications when the Temperature is reduced below the maximum working temperature.
Citation.Title: max surge temperature

Citation.Description: Maximum temperature
Citation.Title: max temperature

Citation.Description: Maximum temperature reached by the system, sensor or equipment
Citation.Title: max temperature reached

Citation.Description: Minimum Storage Temperature
Citation.Title: min storage temperature

Citation.Description: Temperature of gas at orifice meter line when a sample is taken
Citation.Title: orifice meter gas temperature

Citation.Description: Temperature of a specific sensor.
Citation.Title: sensor temperature

Citation.Description: Temperature of the separator when a sample is taken
Citation.Title: separator temperature

Citation.Description: Temperature considered to be "standard", for rates and volumes reported to be measured at Standard Conditions.

Citation.Description: Temperature above ground. Temperature of the atmosphere.

Citation.Description: The temperature of the input material.

Citation.Description: The temperature of the output material

Citation.Description: Computed temperature at some depth in tubing
Citation.Title: vertical lift temperature

Citation.Description: Temperature at the Wellhead with well flowing
Citation.Title: wellhead flowing temperature

Citation.Description: The temperature at the wellhead occurring at the time of the activity being performed on the well.
Citation.Title: wellhead temperature

Citation.Description: A measure of the combined chilling effect of wind and low temperature on living things, also named chill factor, e.g., according to US weather service table, an air temperature of 30 degF with a 10 mi/h corresponds to a "wind-chill" of 22 degF.
