Citation.Title: lwd tool type

Citation.Description: The type of a tool used for Measurement While Drilling.
Citation.Title: mwd tool type

Citation.Description: The type of a Tool usually used in some wireline activity, e.g. CNTA, USIT, AIT, etc.
Citation.Title: wireline tool type

Citation.Description: Indicates how the fluid is pumped into the well e.g. by the casing, the tubing, the annulus Casing-tubing ...
Citation.Title: treatment flow path

Citation.Description: Type of upset in tube or body
Citation.Title: tube upset type

Citation.Description: The string tubular equipment connection number that is at the top. Allowed values are: UNKNOWN, 1st connection, and 2nd connection.
Citation.Title: tubular string connect type

Citation.Description: The location of the super tubular equipment where the sub tubular equipment is attached. Allowed values are: UNKNOWN, attached outside of super string equipment, and attached inside of super string equipment
Citation.Title: tubular string location type

Citation.Description: The type of a Tubular used in some activity or installed in and part of the well structure, e.g. Casing, Production Tubing, etc.
Citation.Title: tubular type

Citation.Description: The type of an unconformity in the Earth subsurface, e.g. Joint, Disconformity, Diastem, etc.
Citation.Title: unconformity type

Citation.Description: The type of relationship between a surface and the ones above (e.g. the surfaces below a Horizon are onlapping.)
Citation.Title: upper surface relation

Citation.Description: The type of an Earth subsurface region or volume, e.g. Formation, Reservoir, Tank, Bed, etc.
Citation.Title: volume type

Citation.Description: Type of liquid meter used to measure the water rate
Citation.Title: water rate meter type

Citation.Description: Type of wavelet used to deconvolve seismic data or to convolve with a basic reflection model to produce synthetic seismic data.
Citation.Title: wavelet type

Citation.Description: Describes what controls the production flow of the well (e.g. constant wellhead pressure, constant flowrate)
Citation.Title: well production control mode

Citation.Description: Characterizes the way a well borehole is projected onto a cross section.
Citation.Title: well projection type

Citation.Description: Type of well test: e.g. Conventional, Horizontal, Interference, etc.
Citation.Title: well test model

Citation.Description: Type of Well Test Model selected
Citation.Title: well test model type

Citation.Description: The type of test conducted on a Well.
Citation.Title: well test type

Citation.Description: Matrix acidizing, Cementing, Acid fracturing, Hydraulic fracturing, Gravel Packing ...
Citation.Title: well treatment type

Citation.Description: A property indicating the purpose of a wellbore (borehole).
Citation.Title: wellbore purpose

Citation.Description: Describes Wellbore storage behavior as either constant, variable (exp), or variable (erf).
Citation.Title: wellbore storage type

Citation.Description: Type of wellhead connection (flange, tree- saver ..); data must identity the mechanical item unambiguously to allow a hydraulic connection e.g. Studded Flange API BX150-15000 psi.
Citation.Title: wellhead connection type

Citation.Description: Classification of the wetting characteristic of the rock, such as Oil Wet or Water Wet.
Citation.Title: wetting type

Citation.Description: The type of a set of zone intervals traversing one or more Boreholes and/or one or more Earth subsurface Volumes.
Citation.Title: zone set type

Citation.Description: Productivity index per unit of length
Citation.Title: unit productivity index

PropertyKind.QuantityClass: PWLS:volume per time per length per pressure

Citation.Description: Unknown property type; used to assert that a specific Property Code cannot be determined from the information provided.
Citation.Title: unknown

Citation.Description: The rate of change of the displacement of a body in time.
Citation.Title: velocity

Citation.Description: The velocity of an acoustic wave; the rate at which the wave travels from one point to another. Used generally for all elastic and seismic waves.
Citation.Title: acoustic velocity

Citation.Description: In seismics, the phase velocity which a wavefront appears to have along a line of geophones. Otherwise, the inverse of the slope of a refraction time-distance curve.
Citation.Title: apparent velocity

Citation.Description: Average velocity of an acoustic wave: the distance between two points divided by the travel time of the compressional wave between those points.
Citation.Title: avg acoustic velocity

Citation.Description: Special usage of Avg_Acoustic_Velocity which deals specifically with the velocity between a reference datum near the surface and some subsurface point; often a vertical path is implied and the velocity is computed as depth divided by seismic travel time.
Citation.Title: avg seismic velocity

Citation.Description: Average velocity in a layer or between two subsurface points; generally applied to a rock layer whose velocity can be considered homogeneous. May be derived from stacking velocity using the Dix equation (or a more refined variant).
Citation.Title: interval velocity

Citation.Description: Velocity of a compressional acoustic wave (Vp).
Citation.Title: compressional velocity

Citation.Description: Acoustic velocity of an acoustic (compressional) wave in fluid.
Citation.Title: fluid compressional velocity

Citation.Description: Acoustic velocity of a compressional wave in a given material or matrix.
Citation.Title: matrix compressional velocity

Citation.Description: Sound velocity of gas at reservoir pressure and temperature. Typical value is 200 m/s.
Citation.Title: gas acoustic velocity

Citation.Description: The velocity with which the energy in a wavetrain travels. In dispersive media, it is the velocity of the envelope of the wavetrain.
Citation.Title: group velocity

Citation.Description: The velocity in the direction of energy transport; in anisotropic media it is different from the direction in which the phase velocity is measured. Also called group velocity.
Citation.Title: ray velocity

Citation.Description: Velocity applied in seismic migration.
Citation.Title: migration velocity

Citation.Description: Converted-wave velocity corresponding to a Compressional wave traveling in one direction and a Shear wave traveling the opposite direction, with conversion at the reflector.
Citation.Title: mode converted velocity

Citation.Description: Average converted-wave velocity from the surface to the reflector. The converted wave velocity is determined from the time taken for the energy to travel in one direction as compressional wave and in the other as shear.
Citation.Title: avg mode converted velocity

Citation.Description: Converted-wave velocity measured over a finite interval, with the interval usually determined by geologic layering. The converted wave velocity is determined from the time taken for the energy to travel in one direction as Compressional wave and in the other as Shear.
Citation.Title: interval mode converted velocity

Citation.Description: Stacking converted-wave velocity, for a wave traveling through layers as a Compressional wave in one direction and a Shear wave in the other. This can be computed from a combined RMS average of the Compressional and Shear interval velocities. In practice it is usually determined directly from velocity analysis on short offset converted wave data.
Citation.Title: stack mode converted velocity

Citation.Description: Sound velocity of live oil at reservoir pressure and temperature. Typical value is 1000 m/s.
Citation.Title: oil acoustic velocity

Citation.Description: The velocity of any given phase (such as a trough) or a wave of single frequency; may differ from Group Velocity due to dispersion in the medium.
Citation.Title: phase velocity

Citation.Description: The velocity of a Rayleigh wave (type of seismic wave propagated along the free surface of a semi-infinite medium.
Citation.Title: rayleigh velocity

Citation.Description: Transit-time weighted root mean square of the interval velocities over a series if intervals.
Citation.Title: rms velocity

Citation.Description: The velocity of a shear wave (Vs); a shear wave is a type of seismic wave in which the particle motion is perpendicular to the direction of propagation; also called S-wave or secondary wave.
Citation.Title: shear velocity

Citation.Description: Average shear wave velocity, from the surface to the reflector. The shear wave velocity is determined from the two-way vertical time taken for the energy to travel to the reflector and back as a Shear wave.
Citation.Title: avg shear velocity

Citation.Description: Interval shear wave velocity, measured over a finite interval, with the interval usually determined by geologic layering.
Citation.Title: interval shear velocity

Citation.Description: Acoustic velocity of a shear wave in a given material or matrix.
Citation.Title: matrix shear velocity

Citation.Description: Stacking shear wave velocity computed from an RMS average of the Shear interval velocities. In practice it is often determined from velocity analysis on Shear wave data, or indirectly from the stacking velocities for Compressional and Converted wave data.
Citation.Title: stack shear velocity

Citation.Description: The velocity determined from velocity analysis based upon normal-moveout measurements.
Citation.Title: stack velocity

Citation.Description: The velocity of a Stoneley wave; a Stoneley wave is a type of seismic wave which is propagated along an interface, such as a tube wave in a borehole.
Citation.Title: stoneley velocity

Citation.Description: (Instantaneous) Velocity at surface reference z=0 (z is time or depth).
Citation.Title: velocity at z0

Citation.Description: Velocity of the medium between the zero-time reference of a particular survey to the Seismic Reference Datum.
Citation.Title: velocity to seismic datum

Citation.Description: Sound velocity in water. Typical value under reservoir conditions is 1550 m/s.
Citation.Title: water acoustic velocity

Citation.Description: Average acoustic velocity of the weathered layer, the near-surface low velocity layer consisting of unconsolidated material and rock in which air rather than water fills the pore space.
Citation.Title: weathering velocity

Citation.Description: Weathering velocity at a CDP.
Citation.Title: weathering velocity cdp

Citation.Description: Cable speed, generally measured at the surface as an approximation of tool speed.
Citation.Title: cable speed

Citation.Description: The rate at which corrosion, a complex chemical or electrochemical process by which metal is destroyed, occurs. For example the rate at which a casing pipe rusts (corrodes).
Citation.Title: corrosion rate

Citation.Description: The velocity of the shock or displacement front.
Citation.Title: displacement velocity

Citation.Description: The rate at which erosion occurs.
Citation.Title: erosion rate

Citation.Description: Flow velocity of fluid.
Citation.Title: flow velocity

Citation.Description: Apparent velocity of the fluid.
Citation.Title: apparent fluid velocity

Citation.Description: The rate at which a fluid bubble, gas or liquid, flows through another fluid, gas or liquid. The Velocity depends on the densities and viscosities of the fluids.
Citation.Title: bubble flow velocity

Citation.Description: The velocity of a flow below which erosional damage to devices such as completion equipment is minimized.
Citation.Title: erosional velocity

Citation.Description: Flow velocity of gas component of fluid.
Citation.Title: gas flow velocity

Citation.Description: Flow velocity of heavy phase component of fluid.
Citation.Title: heavy phase flow velocity

Citation.Description: Flow velocity of light phase component of fluid.
Citation.Title: light phase flow velocity

Citation.Description: Flow velocity of liquid component of fluid.
Citation.Title: liquid flow velocity

Citation.Description: Oil Bubble Velocity
Citation.Title: oil bubble flow velocity

Citation.Description: Flow velocity of oil component of fluid.
Citation.Title: oil flow velocity

Citation.Description: In two-phase flow, the difference between the velocities of the two phases.
Citation.Title: slippage velocity

Citation.Description: Water Bubble Velocity
Citation.Title: water bubble flow velocity

Citation.Description: Flow velocity of water component of fluid.
Citation.Title: water flow velocity

Citation.Description: Liquid flux per area
Citation.Title: liquid flux per area

Citation.Description: NMR surface relaxivity
Citation.Title: nmr surface relaxivity

Citation.Description: Usually used to describe the rate at which a formation is penetrated during drilling operation. In general, the rate at which an equipment penetrates a surface or subsurface volume.
Citation.Title: penetration rate

Citation.Description: Average drilling penetration rate (ROP)
Citation.Title: avg penetration rate

Citation.Description: Speed of an equipment running into (counted positive) or out of the hole (counted negative).
Citation.Title: running speed

Citation.Description: Average Speed of equipment running into (counted positive) or out of the hole (counted negative).
Citation.Title: avg running speed

Citation.Description: The rate at which sedimentation occurs.
Citation.Title: sedimentation rate

Citation.Description: Speed of the tool; logging speed.
Citation.Title: tool speed

Citation.Description: Maximum service speed allowed for, or attained by, a logging tool.
Citation.Title: max tool speed

Citation.Description: Describes the volume per area per million years. E.g. the quantity of hydrocarbons generated in a particular area in a certain timeframe
Citation.Title: volume per area per geologic time

Citation.Description: Velocity of the wind
Citation.Title: wind velocity

Citation.Description: The Beaufort wind scale is a system used to estimate and report wind speeds when no measuring apparatus is available. It was invented in the early 19th century by Admiral Sir Francis Beaufort of the British Navy as a way to interpret winds from conditions at sea, e.g. 5 on the Beaufort scale corresponds to a wind of 17-21 knots and is defined as "Fresh Breeze: Moderate waves (1.8m), many white horses."
Citation.Title: beaufort scale number

Citation.Description: The square of a velocity
Citation.Title: velocity squared

Citation.Description: Normalized derivative of viscosity: -(dv/dp)/v where v=viscosity and p=pressure.
Citation.Title: viscosibility

Citation.Description: Normalized derivative of viscosity for water: -(dv/dp)/v where v=viscosity and p=pressure.
Citation.Title: water viscosibility

Citation.Description: The property of a substance offering internal resistance to flow; a measure of the degree of fluidity.
Citation.Title: viscosity

Citation.Description: Ratio Shear Stress/Shear Rate. Equal to Newtonian Viscosity for Newtonian fluid.
Citation.Title: apparent viscosity

Citation.Description: The viscosity of the fluid filtrate i.e the viscosity of the fluid which crossed the filtering media.
Citation.Title: filtrate viscosity

Citation.Description: The viscosity of a fluid (sample) at specific temperature and pressure conditions.
Citation.Title: fluid viscosity

Citation.Description: Time needed for a given quantity of fluid (generally a quart of mud) to flow into a specified size funnel (3/16 inch id tube of a 12 inch long funnel). Used for drilling fluids.
Citation.Title: funnel viscosity

Citation.Description: The viscosity of a gas at specific temperature and pressure conditions.
Citation.Title: gas viscosity

Citation.Description: The dynamic viscosity of a fluid divided by the density of the fluid.
Citation.Title: kinematic viscosity

Citation.Description: The viscosity of a liquid at specific temperature and pressure conditions.
Citation.Title: liquid viscosity

Citation.Description: Slope of Shear Stress/Shear Rate curve for the Newtonian rheology model (Shear Stress proportional to Shear Rate)
Citation.Title: newtonian viscosity

Citation.Description: The viscosity of oil at specific temperature and pressure conditions.
Citation.Title: oil viscosity

Citation.Description: Apparent viscosity of the Bingham Plastic model : Slope of the curve shear stress vs. shear rate (rheogram). Model equation is Shear_Stress = Yield_Stress + Plastic_Viscosity times Shear_Rate.
Citation.Title: plastic viscosity

Citation.Description: Measure of the internal resistance to fluid flow attributable to the amount, type, and size of solids present in a given fluid. When using the direct-indicating viscometer, it is found by subtracting the 300-rpm reading from the 600-rpm reading of a Fann35 rheometer.
Citation.Title: api plastic viscosity

Citation.Description: Measure of the internal resistance to fluid flow attributable to the amount, type, and size of solids present in a given fluid. The Casson model equation is: SQRT(Shear_Stress) = SQRT(Yield_Stress) + SQRT(Plastic_Viscosity X Shear_Rate)
Citation.Title: casson plastic viscosity

Citation.Description: The viscosity of reservoir fluid at specific temperature and pressure conditions.
Citation.Title: reservoir fluid viscosity

Citation.Description: The viscosity of water at specific temperature and pressure conditions.
Citation.Title: water viscosity

Citation.Description: The optical reflectivity of solid organic constituents of rock, known as vitrinite, which provides an indication of thermal maturity.
Citation.Title: vitrinite reflectance

Citation.Description: Voltage Sweep Rate
Citation.Title: voltage sweep rate

Citation.Description: A measure of the space occupied by a body in cubic units; e.g., cm3, in3, quarts, liters, etc.
Citation.Title: volume

Citation.Description: The volume of the portion of the borehole which lies between the borehole wall and the casing.
Citation.Title: annulus volume

Citation.Description: The volume of the borehole.
Citation.Title: borehole volume

Citation.Description: Cumulative volume of the borehole (integrated over length of borehole).
Citation.Title: cumulative borehole volume

Citation.Description: The estimated volume of the Open Hole used in fluid volume/placement computations
Citation.Title: estimated borehole volume

Citation.Description: Volume of cement.
Citation.Title: cement volume

Citation.Description: Cumulative volume of cement (may be integrated over length of borehole or over time of cementing operation).
Citation.Title: cumulative cement volume

Citation.Description: Volume of fluids produced by a zone or interval since the beginning of the production
Citation.Title: cumulative production volume

Citation.Description: Cumulative condensate production.
Citation.Title: cumulative condensate volume

Citation.Description: Cumulative gas production at standard conditions. At constant BHP or WHP, cumulative volume is not the straightforward sum of volume by RHU but determined by Inverse Laplace transformation.
Citation.Title: cumulative gas volume

Citation.Description: Cumulative oil production at standard conditions. At constant BHP or WHP, cumulative volume is not the straightforward sum of volume by RHU but determined by Inverse Laplace transformation.
Citation.Title: cumulative oil volume

Citation.Description: Cumulative water production at standard conditions.
Citation.Title: cumulative water volume

Citation.Description: The cumulative volume, typically of a fluid.
Citation.Title: cumulative volume

Citation.Description: The cumulative volume of water that encroaches into a reservoir.
Citation.Title: cumulative water influx

Citation.Description: Volume of material remaining in a container after normal emptying procedure, and thus not available for use.
Citation.Title: dead volume

Citation.Description: Volume of fluid used to displace another fluid. In special core analysis, may be expressed as unitless multiple of pore volume.
Citation.Title: displacing fluid volume

Citation.Description: Volume of drilling fluid
Citation.Title: drill fluid volume

Citation.Description: Volume of filtrate, such as recovered from an API Fluid Loss test. API RP13 Section 3
Citation.Title: filtrate volume

Citation.Description: Volume of filtrate produced under high temperature, high pressure (HTHP) conditions.
Citation.Title: hthp filtrate volume

Citation.Description: Volume of filtrate produced under low temperature, low pressure (LTLP) conditions.
Citation.Title: ltlp filtrate volume

Citation.Description: The volume of drilling fluid filtrate which is obtained in a filtration test under specific test conditions; used as an indication of the expected rate of filtrate invasion into the formation during drilling.
Citation.Title: fluid loss

Citation.Description: Volume of fluid.
Citation.Title: fluid volume

Citation.Description: The volume of a mud tank or pit
Citation.Title: mud tank volume

Citation.Description: Fracture permeability - width product of a finite conductivity vertical or horizontal fracture.
Citation.Title: fracture conductivity

Citation.Description: Ratio of fracture conductivity (fracture permeability x average width) to the (matrix permeability x fracture half_length) product. Standard industry acronym : "FCD", S.P.E. preferred form "CfD".
Citation.Title: dimensionless fracture conductivity

Citation.Description: This is a copy of the unit quantity GasProductionVolume, which acts as the parent for other Property instances
Citation.Title: gas production volume

Citation.Description: Normalized gas cumulative per number of fractures
Citation.Title: gas production volume per number of fractures

Citation.Description: Total rock volume from a top reservoir surface to a contact, usually the oil-water contact
Citation.Title: gross rock volume

Citation.Description: Volume of gas accumulated prior to the beginning of the measurement period.
Citation.Title: initial gas volume

Citation.Description: Total volume of in situ gas in the reservoir.
Citation.Title: initial in situ gas volume

Citation.Description: Total volume of in situ oil in the reservoir.
Citation.Title: initial in situ oil volume

Citation.Description: Volume of oil accumulated prior to the beginning of the measurement period.
Citation.Title: initial oil volume

Citation.Description: Volume of water accumulated prior to the beginning of the measurement period.
Citation.Title: initial water volume

Citation.Description: Estimate of the volume of a kick (influx of fluid into the wellbore) at bottom hole conditions which can be shut in and circulated out without breaking the formation
Citation.Title: kick tolerance volume

Citation.Description: This is a copy of the unit quantity LiquidProductionVolume, which acts as the parent for other Property instances
Citation.Title: liquid production volume

Citation.Description: Normalized liquid cumulative per number of fractures
Citation.Title: liquid production volume per number of fractures

Citation.Description: Normalized oil cumulative per number of fractures
Citation.Title: oil production volume per number of fractures

Citation.Description: Normalized water cumulative per number of fractures
Citation.Title: water production volume per number of fractures

Citation.Description: The volume of material in a porous system that does not include the volume of the pores.
Citation.Title: matrix volume

Citation.Description: The maximum volume not to be exceeded for a container (Tank, Mud Pit)
Citation.Title: max volume

Citation.Description: Amount of 0.02 normal (N/50) standard sulfuric acid required in order to turn the color of methyl orange indicator solution from yellow to pink when determining methyl orange alkalinity of the mud filtrate, Mf, API RP13 Section 8, Chemical Analysis.
Citation.Title: mf titration volume

Citation.Description: Volume of fluid which can be contained in the vessel
Citation.Title: nom liquid capacity

Citation.Description: The product of permeability and thickness of the body acting as a conduit.
Citation.Title: permeability thickness

Citation.Description: Thickness of the permeable net pay portion of the zone i.e., the product of the Net Pay Thickness and Net Pay Average Permeability
Citation.Title: net pay permeability thickness

Citation.Description: The product of the Net Reservoir Thickness and Net Reservoir Average Permeability.
Citation.Title: net reservoir permeability thickness

Citation.Description: Total permeability-thickness [= kh(1) + kh(2)] for a vertical interference test
Citation.Title: total permeability thickness

Citation.Description: A permeability length used in rel per calculations
Citation.Title: permeability length

Citation.Description: Amount of 0.02 normal (N/50) standard sulfuric acid required in order to turn the color of phenolphthalein indicator solution from pink to colorless when determining phenolphthalein alkalinity of the mud filtrate, Pf, API RP13 Section 8, Chemical Analysis.
Citation.Title: pf titration volume

Citation.Description: Amount of 0.02 normal (N/50) standard sulfuric acid required in order to turn the color of phenolphthalein indicator solution from pink to colorless when determining phenolphthalein alkalinity of the mud, Pm, API RP13 Section 8, Chemical Analysis.
Citation.Title: pm titration volume

Citation.Description: The volume within a geologic volume that describes the connected void space within the matrix of rock.
Citation.Title: pore volume

Citation.Description: The pore volume of a reservoir occupied by hydrocarbons in either the vapor or liquid phase.
Citation.Title: hydrocarbon pore volume

Citation.Description: Available volume of fluids below testing valve. The rat hole is the section of the borehole running from the tester valve to the effective bottom of the well. The calculation of this volume is not straight-forward as the rat hole is not generally empty.
Citation.Title: rat hole volume

Citation.Description: Volume of material which remains (e.g. remaining volume to be pumped)
Citation.Title: remaining volume

Citation.Description: Volume of fluids produced from a reservoir
Citation.Title: reservoir production volume

Citation.Description: Volume of material pumped during a stage of an activity.
Citation.Title: stage volume

Citation.Description: Volume of a pump stroke
Citation.Title: stroke volume

Citation.Description: Total volume of the surface lines equipment
Citation.Title: surface lines volume

Citation.Description: Transmissibility
Citation.Title: transmissibility

Citation.Description: Dead volume including the surface treating lines to be pumped to move the treating fluid down to formation. In cementing it is the volume (through casing/tubing/ drillpipe) up to the landing collar; in acidizing it is the tubing volume to perforations
Citation.Title: treatment displacement volume

Citation.Title: gas production volume per perforation length

Citation.Title: liquid production volume per perforation length

Citation.Title: water production volume per perforation length

Citation.Description: The measure of volume of mud filtrate lost to the formation per linear length of borehole, usually given in U.S. gal/ft.

Citation.Description: This is a copy of the unit quantity VolumePerMass, which acts as the parent for other Property instances

Citation.Description: Adsorbed volume of hydrocarbon components per rock mass

Citation.Description: This is a copy of the unit quantity volume per mass per time, which acts as the parent for other Property instances

Citation.Description: (Fracturing) Measure of the capability of a fluid flowing in front of a porous media to build up a filter cake inhibiting the fluid leakoff through the porous media. Non RPP66 unit :length/(time)**1/2 e.g. ft/min**1/2
Citation.Title: wall building coefficient

Citation.Description: Bandwidth rating bias in depth domain. See Bandwidth_Rating_Bias

Citation.Description: Bandwidth rating debias in depth domain. See Bandwidth_Rating_Debias

Citation.Description: Central frequency in the depth domain

Citation.Description: Dominant Wavenumber in depth domain. Reciprocal of distance between successive peaks or troughs.
